[1
Date: Sun, 19 Sep 1999 14:29:06 +0700
From: Daniel Libraty <dlibraty@mozart.inet.co.th>

Regarding the comment that tertiary syphilis affects the cerebellum.
Actually, the gait disturbance classically described in tertiary or
neurosyphilis is due to posterior sensory column degeneration in the spinal
cord (tabes dorsalis). As syphilis is "the great imitator", it probably
has produced cerebellar dysfunction (in probably the gummatous or
meningovascular form); however, cerebellar involvement is not typical of
neurosyphilis. One infectious disease that has been classically noted to
result in cerebellar ataxia is varicella encephalitis. This is generally
noted during or just after the encephalitis, and is felt to be due to
post-infectious demyelination.
--
Daniel H. Libraty, M.D.
University of Massachusetts and
USAMC-AFRIMS, Department of Virology
Bangkok, Thailand
e-mail: dlibraty@mozart.inet.co.th
