[2
Date: Mon, 20 Sep 1999 13:56:17 +1000
From: Jeff McKee <j.mckee@mailbox.uq.edu.au>

Canine Distemper virus (CDV), a morbillivirus, causes cerebellar lesions in
infected dogs, usually in association with panencephalitis, myelitis, optic
tract involvement and multisystem disease. Cerebellar lesions typically
include Purkinje and glial cell degeneration with mononuclear cell
infiltrate, eosinophilic inclusion bodies and
demyelination. Clinical signs specifically referable to cerebellar disease
do occur but more commonly these are swamped by signs associated
panencephalitis and other systems failure. The disease is highly
contagious, has a worldwide distribution and is invariably fatal. Most
canids, some mustelids, some pinnnipeds and some felids are susceptible.
Complete clinical, epidemiological and histopathological descriptions can
be found in standard Veterinary texts.
Other related morbilliviruses such as the phocid distemper viruses and
cetacean distemper viruses can cause similar clinical syndromes in their
hosts but I am unsure about cerebellar involvement.
Cerebellar lesions are also reported in cats with feline panleukopenia
(parvovirus) infection.
--
Jeff McKee
e-mail: j.mckee@mailbox.uq.edu.au
