[3
Date: Mon, 20 Sep 1999 10:20:11 -0400
From: Peter Lusis <plusis@kemptvillec.uoguelph.ca>

A very brief search of veterinary pathology texts for animal diseases with
predominantly cerebellar involvement included: enterovirus (avian
encephalomyelitis, Teschen disease, porcine encephalomyelitis), togavirus
(louping ill) and possibly [rhabdovirus rabies (Purkinje cells are one of
the most common sites of Negri bodies). In addition, prenatal cerebellar
hypoplasia is caused by parvoviruses (feline and murine), togaviruses
(bovine virus diarrhea, Border disease and hog cholera), and arenaviruses
(lymphocytic choriomeningitis) in rats. Cerebellitis is also not uncommon
with many viral, bacterial and rickettsial diseases with generalized CNS
involvement.
--
Peter Lusis DVM, MSc
University of Guelph Laboratory Services Division
Kemptville Animal Health Laboratory
Kemptville, Ontario, Canada KOG IJO
e-mail: plusis@kemptvillec.uoguelph.ca
