[4
Date: Mon, 20 Sep 1999 10:59:28 -0500
From: Janet Welter <welter@rarc.wisc.edu>

Feline panleukopenia virus (FLV), a parvovirus, also targets cerebellar
tissue in domestic cats either in utero or during the early postnatal
period (up to 9 days after birth). Both the external cell granular layer
and Purkinje cells are disrupted irreversibly with degeneration of the
granuloprival layers. Clinical signs are typical of cerebellar hypoplasia,
with ataxia and intention tremors. Live attenuated FLV vaccine can also
cause cerebellar hypoplasia in kittens vaccinated before 3 weeks of age, or
kittens born to queens vaccinated during gestation.
Reference:
Podell, M. 1994. Rabies and other viral diseases of the nervous system, p
511-512. In R. G. Sherding (ed.), The Cat: Diseases and Clinical
Management. Churchill Livingstone, New York.
--
Janet Welter, DVM, MPH, PhD
e-mail: welter@rarc.wisc.edu
